---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/Nav.astro";

const description =
  "Why Sphere is called Sphere: a short note on Habermas, Benjamin, fragments, constellations, and agent-readable public knowledge.";
---

<Base
  title="Why Sphere is called Sphere"
  description={description}
  ogTitle="Why Sphere is called Sphere"
  ogDescription="A short note on Habermas, Benjamin, fragments, constellations, and agent-readable public knowledge."
  ogType="article"
  path="/notes/public-sphere/"
>
  <Nav variant="page" />

  <main class="note-page">
    <article class="note">
      <p class="eyebrow">Note on public knowledge</p>
      <h1>Why Sphere is called Sphere</h1>
      <p class="note-lede">
        Sphere is named after the public sphere: the shared space where
        information becomes visible, debatable, citable, contestable, and
        accountable.
      </p>

      <section>
        <h2>Habermas: publicness as infrastructure</h2>
        <p>
          Habermas gives Sphere its civic intuition. Public knowledge is not
          only content that exists somewhere. It becomes public when people can
          encounter it, question it, cite it, challenge it, and use it to form
          judgment.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI agents are becoming intermediaries in that process. They read,
          summarize, retrieve, rank, and recommend. If they mediate access to
          knowledge, then public knowledge needs machine-readable conditions:
          provenance, rights, citation, access policy, and accountability.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Benjamin: fragments and constellations</h2>
        <p>
          Benjamin gives Sphere its form. Knowledge does not always arrive as a
          closed system. It often appears as fragments: quotations, notes,
          images, traces, documents, claims, data points, and citations.
        </p>
        <p>
          A fragment is not weak because it is partial. It becomes meaningful
          through relation. Fragments can be arranged, juxtaposed, cited, and
          read as constellations. This is why Sphere treats a fragment as an
          atomic unit, but never as an isolated one.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Technical translation</h2>
        <p>
          In Sphere, the theory becomes infrastructure. A fragment is a bounded
          unit of agent-readable knowledge. It can include Markdown content,
          source files, datasets, media, license metadata, access policy,
          provenance, and semantic relations to other fragments.
        </p>
        <p>
          Relations make fragments public in a stronger sense. A fragment can
          cite, support, extend, update, contradict, derive from, or belong to a
          constellation. The goal is not simply to expose text to machines, but
          to preserve the conditions under which knowledge can be trusted,
          questioned, reused, and attributed.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Why now</h2>
        <p>
          The web was built for human readers, then crawled by machines. The
          next public sphere will be partly mediated by agents. Sphere starts
          from a modest question: what should a piece of public knowledge look
          like when the first reader may be an AI system?
        </p>
        <p>
          The answer is not a paywall or a black box. It is a fragment with
          explicit structure, rights, provenance, relations, and signals that
          help publishers understand whether their knowledge is ready to be read
          by agents.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>
</Base>
